Bring a #medium pot{} of salted @water{} to a boil. Wash and dry produce.

Trim and remove strings from @sugar snap peas{4%ounce}. Quarter @lime{1}. Roughly chop @cilantro{1/4%ounce}.

Once water is boiling, add @lo mein noodles{4.5%ounce} to #pot. Cook, stirring occasionally, until al dente, ~{5-7%minutes}. Drain and set aside.

While noodles cook, rinse @shrimp{10%ounce} under cold water, then pat dry. Season all over with @garlic powder{1%teaspoon}.

Drizzle @cooking oil{} in a hot #large pan{}. Add shrimp, snap peas, and @bok choy and napa cabbage{4%ounce}. Cook, stirring occasionally, until veggies are browned and tender and shrimp are opaque and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Stir @sweet soy glaze{4%tablespoon}, @sweet Thai chili sauce{1%ounce}, @butter{1%tbsp}, and @Korean chili flakes{1%teaspoon} to taste into pan with shrimp and veggies. Cook, stirring, until coated, ~{1-2%minutes}. Remove from heat.

> For 4 servings, use 2 TBSP butter instead of 1 TBSP.

Stir in drained noodles and juice from two lime wedges until thoroughly coated and combined. Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. (For 4, transfer everything to a #large bowl{} to combine.)

Garnish lo mein with @peanuts{1/2%ounce}(chopped) and cilantro. Serve with remaining lime wedges on the side.

> For an extra-nutty crunch, toast peanuts in a hot dry pan!

> Shrimp are fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.